{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696404/1930122401/0827.xml":{"full_text":"Financial Market News, Stocks, Bonds, Commodities and Comment\nDISTRICT TRADE\nDULL DUE TO\nHOLIDAY\nProduce Prices Remain Un\nchanged With Signs of Trade\nRecord Smashing of Sales\nDullness of trade in Washing\nton markets and on the Washing\nton Stock Exchange was indica\ntive of the slowness of trading\nthat always occurs during a holi\nday.\nMany of the buys during the\ntrading on the local exchange\nwere of an Investment nature al\nthough several of the deals put\nthrough during the session showed\nthat a slight amount of specula\ntion cm a future rise was included\nin the buying.\nProduce prices here remained\nunchanged with enormous sales\nreported. Farmers in the retail\nmarket were able to clear the\ngreater majority of their goods\nbefore midday with sales steadily\nmounting.\nThere was every indication that\na steadiness of trade weuld be\nshown throughout the holiday sea\nson with the probability that it\nwould continue through the new\nyear.\nWith holiday buying maintain\ning a brisk pace which promises to\nsurpass in volume if not in cash\nreceipts .the record of a year ago,\nand with members of 1931 Christ\nmas Savings Clubs of the various\nDistrict banks starting these spe\ncial accounts in even larger num\nber and amounts than they did\nlast year when they established\nan all-time record for Washing\nton, the air of depression reported\nas prevailing in most other large\ncities of the country does not\napply here, bankers and mer\nchants assert.\nAlthough the unit of sales in\nretail stores is expected to be at\nleast 10 per cent larger than a\nyear ago a drop in receipts is\nanticipated because prices have\nfallen in the past 2 months at\nan even more rapid rate.\nAccounts Growing\nPermanent savings accounts of\nthe District banks are also re\nported as growing. Not only have\nlarge numbers of persons receiv\ning Christmas savings checks de\nposited a portion of these\namounts in previously established\npermanent savings accounts but\nothers have used the money to\nstart new permanent accounts.\nAlthough banks are not pre\npared yet to give definite figures\nthose in charge of the Christmas\nSavings Clubs departments in\nmany of the banks state that\nmore persons are enrolling in the\nclubs this year than had signed\nup last year in the corresponding\nperiod and that the average sum\nwould be larger than before.\nAlmost $8,000,000 in savings\nand interest was paid out the\nfirst of this month to approxi\nmately 92,000 individual deposi\ntors members of Christmas Sav\nings clubs conducted by the Dis\ntrict banks.\nMrs. Lanier P. McLachlen has\nbeen appointed chairman and\nMrs. Edward J. McQuade, vice\nchairman of the ladies* committee\nof the District of Columbia Bank\ners Association 1931 annual con\nvention to be held at Hot Springs\nnext June. In announcing the\nappointments Frederick R. H.\nSiddons, chairman of the general\ncommittee, also named the fol\nlowing members of the ladies\u2019\ncommittee:\nMesdames Claude H. Wood\nward, Frederick H. Cox, Hilleary\nC. Hoskinson, C. F. Jacobson,\nLuther E. Schreiner, Albert S.\nGatley, C, H. Pope, George O.\nVass, Frederick P. H. Siddons, J.\nFrank White and Wilmer J.\nWaller.\nSanta Claus paid a visit to the\nChristmas party held at the Dis\ntrict National Bank yesterday\nafternoon.\nWith all the bank employes\ngathered around the tree, Santa,\nImpersonated by Col. R. N. Har\nper, and Miss Florence Kelly, dis\ntributed gifts to all.\nPresident Joshua Evans, Jr.,\nwas presented with a brief case\nby the employes. All the officers\nof the bank made addresses.\nNEW YORK LIVE STOCK\nNEW YORK, Dec. 24.\u2014Live stock.\nCattle \u2014Receipts, 250 head; all directs.\nVealers and calves\u2014Receipts, 420 head;\nall directs.\nHoge\u2014Receipts, 3,280 head; all di\nrects.\nSheep\u2014Receipts, 8.040 head; all di\nrects- No live stock on sale. Prices\nhominal.\nO